OkCupid Dating Profile Analysis¶

By Ritvik Yaragudipati and Renee Sen

OkCupid is a free popular online dating application created in 2004 that uses a matching algorithm to help users find potential partners. OkCupid asks users to fill out a questionnaire and create a profile with personal information and photos, which is then used to find compatible matches. The website has a variety of features, such as the ability to message other users and attend events, to help users connect with potential partners. It is owned by Match Group, which is also who owns the other popular dating applications, like Tinder, Hinge, and others.

The dataset being used in this analysis contains 60,000 records of anonymous user answers to the questionnaire from 2012. It includes data of basic information like gender, orientation, to more personalized information in the profile text column.

This tutorial will lead you through the process of cleaning up the data (dealing with different human responses, gibberish text in the columns, renaming columns/responses for ease of understanding, etc.), and then analyzing the data through the use of visuals. With this information, we will determine/predict what type of factors are most successful in creating a match. We hope that our readers will come out being aware of what may be more important to emphasize in profiles.

This of course is not to dissuade users from personalizing their profiles in the way they want or cause them change themselves to fit other's standards. This data is from 10 years ago, so it would be interesting to see how the dating scene was back then compared to now. What factors would lead to relationships from 10 years ago? Future work would be to compare a more recent dataset.

Feel free to challenge the predictions!

We will begin by importing the libraries we need. This will include libaries that can help us with data cleaning to libraries that can help us visualize and then create our predictions.

Take the time to go onto the libraries API to understand the different functions there are and what they do.

Part 2: Data Cleaning¶

When we load in the data we will see that a lot of the data inside the table needs a lot of cleaning or changing to make it easier for us to work with.

In our data set, we have multiple essay categories that could essentially just go into one category. So, we did exactly that. We located all the columns with essays, and combined them into one category called "profile text".

We also needed to make sure that if there was any profile texts that had "NA", that we would explicitly put "No Info". While we could've left it alone, it would be more detailed for us to make it clear that it had no info.

Combining the essays also can give us another metric that we can use for analysis: "Total Words". How much do people actually write in their essays?

In [46]:
# Combining essays into 1 profile text
data["profile text"] = (data["essay0"].str.cat(data.iloc[:,22:-1].astype(str), sep=" "))

# dropping all the extra columns
data=data.drop(data.iloc[:,21:-1], axis=1)
# if there are any NA columns
data["profile text"]=data["profile text"].fillna("No info")

# creating a column for the total amount of words in all the essays
data["Total Words"]=data["profile text"].str.split().str.len()

Next we can see we have a status column. This column is important as it will serve to be what we are predicting based one certain factors. There are multiple ways to convey status, so it would be useful to narrow it down to just single and taken.

We can do that by replacing all the values that represent single to single and replace all the values that represent taken to taken.

We will also make sure to store these rows specific to single or taken for later use in testing our predictions.

In [47]:
# We want to sepreate our data between people who are single and people who are taken

# looking at the different values
data['status'].unique()

# both single and available mean single 
singlevalues = ['single', 'available']
# both seeing someone and married mean taken
takenvalues = ['seeing someone', 'married']

# gettig all the values that are single/taken and putting into a mask
mask = data['status'].isin(singlevalues)
mask2 = data['status'].isin(takenvalues)
single = data.loc[mask]
taken = data.loc[mask2]

# replacing all availables with single
single.replace('available', 'single', inplace = True)

# replacing all seeing someone and married with taken
taken.replace('seeing someone', 'taken', inplace = True)
taken.replace('married', 'taken', inplace = True)

print('single: ', single['status'].unique() , 
      '\nTaken: ', taken['status'].unique())

single:  ['single'] 
Taken:  ['taken']

We also want to one hot encode the following values for our data analysis:

  1. sign signifiance
  2. religion
  3. drinks
  4. income

We will include a dictionary of the encoded values for reference in the future

What is one-hot encoding and why are we using it? Here is a good resource to quickly understand what it is: One-Hot Encoding

This will help improve our predictions later on when we do our machine learning algorithm.

In [52]:
# We can one hot encode the columns with multiple text variations for better statistical results 
encoded = ['sign', 'religion', 'drinks', 'income']
mappings = {}
for arg in encoded:
  le = LabelEncoder()
  # # fit the encoder to the DataFrame column
  le.fit(data[arg])
  # apply the encoding to the column and store the transformed values
  arg2  = arg + '_value'
  data[arg2] = le.transform(data[arg])
  tmp = {i: cat for i, cat in enumerate(le.classes_)}
  mappings[f"{arg}"] = tmp



#creating a single mapping dictionary of all the column values
mappings

Part 4: Hypothesis Testing¶

We want to see what category has the largest effect in predicting the status of an user. To do this we will do some hypothesis testing. We will take a look at the correlations and then take a look at the p-values of each category. Lets start by stating all the hypothesis

Diet

Ho: Diet has no effect in predicting status of an user

Ha: Diet has an effect in predicting status of an user

Drinks

Ho: Drinking has no effect in predicting status of an user

Ha: Drinking has an effect in predicting status of an user

Religion

Ho: Religion has no effect in predicting status of an user

Ha: Religion has an effect in predicting status of an user

Sign

Ho: Sign has no effect in predicting status of an user

Ha: Sign has an effect in predicting status of an user

Income

Ho: Income has no effect in predicting status of an user

Ha: Income has an effect in predicting status of an user

We will begin by looking at the correlation between the user status and the choice of these categories: diet, drinks, religion, sign, and income.

First, lets take a look at how many rows in these specific columns contain null. We decided that the best course of action is to drop them.

To do this, we can find out how many nulls we currently have.

The status column has a unknown value that basically represents null, so lets replace that with a null so that those rows can drop as well.

Now, lets calculate our p-values for our hypothesis and determine whether we will end up rejecting or failing to reject the null hypothesis. We will be using a spearman rank correlation coefficient to get the p-values. This is because we have a numerical value and a categorical value and this will be able to accomodate for that. A pearson correlation coefficient, which may be more commonly used, deals with only continous values.

In [70]:

K Nearest Neighbhor¶

For our algorithm, we will be implementing a K Nearest Neighbhor. K-Nearest Neighbors (KNN) is a simple and effective classification algorithm that can be used for a variety of tasks. It works by finding the K nearest data points in the training set for a given sample in the test set, and then predicting the label of the sample based on the labels of its nearest neighbors. KNN has several attractive properties, including that it is easy to implement and understand, and it often performs well even with relatively small amounts of training data.

Using KNN for classification on the OK Cupid data will be beneficial if the data is structured in a way that allows KNN to make accurate predictions. For example, if the data points in the training set are well separated, such that each class is surrounded by points from the same class, then KNN may be able to accurately predict the labels of the test set samples based on their nearest neighbors. In addition, KNN may be particularly well suited for this data set if the relationships between the features and the labels are relatively simple and non-linear, as KNN is known to work well with such data.

Lets now do a K Nearest Neighbor (KNN) algorithm on this data.

In [71]:
training_data, validation_data, training_labels, validation_labels = train_test_split(df_features_all, df_labels, test_size = 0.2, random_state = 100)
accuracies = []
for k in range(1,25):
    knn = KNeighborsClassifier(n_neighbors=k)
    knn.fit(training_data, training_labels.values.ravel())
    knn_score = knn.score(validation_data, validation_labels)
    accuracies.append(knn_score)

#
plt.plot(range(1,25), accuracies)
plt.xlabel('k')
plt.ylabel('Validation accuracy')
plt.title('Classifier for Status')
plt.show()
In [72]:
print(max(accuracies)) # This is the max of this graph, gets hit around a k-value of 8.

0.962762356127285

Lets walk through how this code works.

The data is first split into training and validation sets using the train_test_split function from the sklearn.model_selection module. The function takes in the features (df_features_all) and labels (df_labels) of the data, and the desired size of the validation set (specified as a fraction of the total data with the test_size parameter, in this case 0.2 or 20%). The random_state parameter is used to specify a seed for the random number generator, so that the same split is obtained every time the code is run.

The KNN classifier is then trained and evaluated in a loop, where the number of neighbors (k) is varied from 1 to 24. For each value of k, a KNN classifier object is created using KNeighborsClassifier from the sklearn.neighbors module, and the classifier is trained on the training data using the fit method. The classifier's performance is then evaluated on the validation data using the score method, which returns the accuracy of the classifier (i.e., the fraction of correctly classified samples). The accuracy is stored in a list called accuracies.

Finally, a plot is generated showing how the validation accuracy changes with the number of neighbors. The plot is created using the plot function from the matplotlib.pyplot module, which takes in the range of k values and the corresponding accuracies as its arguments. The plot is labeled and given a title using the xlabel, ylabel, and title functions, respectively. The plot is then displayed using the show function.

Random Forest¶

We can also try using a random forest calssifier as another method for determining accuracy.

A random forest is a type of machine learning model that is used for classification and regression tasks. It is an ensemble learning method, which means that it is composed of multiple individual models (called decision trees) that are trained on different subsets of the data and then combined to make predictions.

Random forests are useful for a variety of tasks, including predicting the likelihood of an event based on a set of predictors (e.g., whether a user will respond to a message on a dating site), estimating the value of a continuous variable (e.g., predicting how compatible two users are based on their profiles), and identifying patterns and relationships in data (e.g., identifying factors that predict whether a user will initiate a conversation).

One of the benefits of using a random forest is that it can handle high-dimensional and complex data sets, and can effectively handle data that includes both categorical and numerical variables. It can also handle missing data and handle imbalanced data sets (where one class is much more prevalent than the other).

In the context of the OK Cupid data set, a random forest model might be useful for predicting which users are most likely to get in a relationship. It could also be used to identify factors that predict compatibility or success in relationships, such as diet type, religion, income, and more

In [73]:
forest = RandomForestClassifier(random_state = 1)
forest.fit(training_data, training_labels.values.ravel())
print(forest.score(validation_data, validation_labels))

0.9596027984653577

This number is also pretty big! But it seems our KNN algorithm does a better job at predicting than Random Forest.

Conclusion¶

Based on the results of a statistical analysis, it appears that diet is the most significant predictor of the chance of being in a relationship. This conclusion is supported by the fact that the p-value for diet was the lowest among all of the predictors, indicating that the effect of diet on the chance of being in a relationship is statistically significant.

This suggests that diet plays an important role in determining the chance of being in a relationship, and that it is an important factor to consider when trying to predict this outcome. It is important to note, however, that other factors may also be important in predicting the chance of being in a relationship (such as drinking, income , religion ,etc), and that the relative importance of these factors may vary depending on the specific context and the population being studied.
